
***********  Simple description of Layout of files, etc. ************

IDL_orig:

  The original IDL code from the noone_diagram.zip archive that you sent.

TryingThings:

  Just some files of things I tried and notes all related to how to get
  things going in Python to match what IDL doe.



EarlyStageTranslation:

  Some of the earlier parts of the translation, so some IDL and some
  Python intermingled. This was when I was still working on to translate
  code involving IDL findgen and fltarr, etc.



Python:

  The location with the translated code and some other information. The
  files "Notes" has some random notes on some of the issues encountered.

  The subdirectory "Information" has some scaled up versions of Fig 2
  with some notes added, such as which of isoeqlsat, isomixline, or
  isoraysat was used to produce which curve in Fig 2. File "plot_info"
  tries to look at the colour and line style information and relating it
  to the top-level routine "noone_curves". Fig_2_descriptions pulls
  apart the caption for Fig_2 into the pieces for each of the plotted
  curves. Fig_2_big.pdf is Fig_2 much enlarged, and annotated with which
  of the iso... routines was used. Since I do not have a colour printer,
  the colour of each curve is indicated by O, C, or M in a square box.

  The directory with the "final" Python code is "saved_Python", and this
  directory is also tar archived in the file "saved_Python.tgz".

  All the .py files are concatenated into "all.py" for loading in one
  go, and the "cat" command is in the bash script Make_all.

  The top-level Python file that calls all the various iso... routines
  is in "noone_curves.py" but this does not execute completely, because
  the variables "i80" and "ifrz" are not defined at least that I can
  find. We should talk about that.

  The SimplePlots subdirectory is really preliminary testing, where I
  just ran the first two isomixline calls from noone_curves.py, just
  using "script.py" and cut-past commands to python. I then just
  cut-pasted the data from the arrays (I had set "nn" down to 20 to make
  things smaller) and then just used vi to create data files that I
  could plot with gnuplot using the little file First_go.plt. The result
  was the basic plot in the qh2odeldmix_evap.ps or the PDF version
  qh2odeldmix_evap.pdf.


